    <!-- Main Content -->
    <div class="container">
        <!-- Science-based Nutrition Section -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>The Science of Nutrition for Athletes</h2>
            <p class="section-intro">Understanding the scientific principles behind nutrition can help optimize your training and recovery. Below are key findings from recent research:</p>
            
            <div class="nutrition-grid">
                <div class="nutrition-card research-card">
                    <h3>Protein Timing and Distribution</h3>
                    <p>Research shows that distributing protein intake evenly throughout the day (20-40g per meal) maximizes muscle protein synthesis more effectively than consuming the same amount in fewer, larger servings.</p>
                    <div class="research-link">
                        <i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i>
                        <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24257722/" target="_blank">Mamerow et al. (2014). Journal of Nutrition</a>
                    </div>
                    <div class="key-finding">
                        Consuming 25-30g of protein per meal stimulates maximal protein synthesis in most individuals.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="nutrition-card research-card">
                    <h3>Carbohydrate Periodization</h3>
                    <p>Strategic manipulation of carbohydrate intake based on training phases can enhance metabolic flexibility and performance. This approach involves timing higher carb intake around intense training sessions.</p>
                    <div class="research-link">
                        <i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i>
                        <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29453741/" target="_blank">Impey et al. (2018). Journal of Sports Sciences</a>
                    </div>
                    <div class="key-finding">
                        "Train low, compete high" strategies can improve fat oxidation while preserving high-intensity performance.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="nutrition-card research-card">
                    <h3>Fasting and Performance</h3>
                    <p>Intermittent fasting protocols may provide metabolic benefits, but timing is crucial. Research suggests avoiding fasting before high-intensity or strength-focused training sessions.</p>
                    <div class="research-link">
                        <i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i>
                        <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27710558/" target="_blank">Tinsley & Willoughby (2016). Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</a>
                    </div>
                    <div class="key-finding">
                        Fasting may enhance certain metabolic pathways but can impair performance in high-intensity training if not properly implemented.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Evidence-Based Supplements Section -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Evidence-Based Supplements</h2>
            <p class="section-intro">These supplements have substantial scientific support for their efficacy and safety when used appropriately:</p>
            
            <div class="nutrition-grid">
                <div class="nutrition-card supplement-card">
                    <h3>Creatine Monohydrate</h3>
                    <p><strong>Efficacy Rating:</strong> <span class="rating">★★★★★</span></p>
                    <p>Consistently shown to increase strength, power output, and muscle mass when combined with resistance training. Beneficial for both short-duration, high-intensity exercise and recovery.</p>
                    <div class="dosage-info">
                        <h4>Research-Based Dosage:</h4>
                        <p>Loading phase: 20g/day for 5-7 days (split into 4 doses)<br>Maintenance: 3-5g/day</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="research-link">
                        <i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i>
                        <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28615996/" target="_blank">Kreider et al. (2017). Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="nutrition-card supplement-card">
                    <h3>Beta-Alanine</h3>
                    <p><strong>Efficacy Rating:</strong> <span class="rating">★★★★☆</span></p>
                    <p>Improves performance in high-intensity exercise lasting 1-4 minutes through increased muscle carnosine levels, enhancing buffering capacity against exercise-induced acidosis.</p>
                    <div class="dosage-info">
                        <h4>Research-Based Dosage:</h4>
                        <p>3.2-6.4g/day (divided into multiple smaller doses to minimize paresthesia)</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="research-link">
                        <i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i>
                        <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30997908/" target="_blank">Trexler et al. (2015). Sports Medicine</a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="nutrition-card supplement-card">
                    <h3>Vitamin D</h3>
                    <p><strong>Efficacy Rating:</strong> <span class="rating">★★★★☆</span></p>
                    <p>Important for bone health, immune function, and potentially muscle function. Deficiency is common in athletes, especially those training indoors or in northern latitudes.</p>
                    <div class="dosage-info">
                        <h4>Research-Based Dosage:</h4>
                        <p>1,000-2,000 IU/day (higher doses may be necessary to correct deficiency, based on blood work)</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="research-link">
                        <i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i>
                        <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29273683/" target="_blank">Owens et al. (2018). European Journal of Sport Science</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Nutrition Strategies Section -->
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Periodized Nutrition Strategies by Training Phase</h2>
            
            <table class="periodization-table">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Training Phase</th>
                        <th>Protein</th>
                        <th>Carbohydrates</th>
                        <th>Fat</th>
                        <th>Key Considerations</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Hypertrophy</td>
                        <td>1.6-2.2g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>4-7g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>0.5-1.5g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>Slight caloric surplus (+200-500 kcal); emphasis on post-workout nutrition</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Strength</td>
                        <td>1.6-2.0g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>3-5g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>0.8-1.5g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>Focus on recovery between high CNS-demand sessions; maintenance calories</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Fat Loss</td>
                        <td>2.0-2.4g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>2-4g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>0.8-1.2g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>Moderate caloric deficit (-300-500 kcal); higher protein to preserve lean mass</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Performance</td>
                        <td>1.4-1.8g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>5-10g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>0.8-1.0g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>Carb loading pre-competition; emphasis on fueling for workouts</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Maintenance</td>
                        <td>1.6-1.8g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>3-5g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>0.8-1.2g/kg/day</td>
                        <td>Caloric balance; focus on nutrient density and meal consistency</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
            <div class="research-note">
                <i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i>
                <p>Based on research from the International Society of Sports Nutrition position stands (Kerksick et al., 2018) and the American College of Sports Medicine guidelines.</p>
                <div class="research-link">
                    <i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i>
                    <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29642608/" target="_blank">Kerksick et al. (2018). Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        
